Sheryl and Joshua,

I did some additional research regarding the special election to treat char=
itable distributions made in 2021 as paid in 2020.  You will need to file a=
n additional form 1041A.  It includes a balance sheet for the trust.  I nee=
d to know the book value of assets as of 01/01/2020 and 12/31/2021.  My und=
erstanding is that the only account in the name of the trust is the Bank of=
 America account(s).  If that is correct, I need to know the cash balance a=
s of 01/01/2020 and as of 12/31/2020.  Also, let me know if there were othe=
r assets or if the trust had any liabilities or accrued expenses at the end=
 of 2020.

We will not file 2020 as a final return for the following reasons.


1.       We will need to file a 2021 tax year Form 1041A showing the charit=
able distributions actually paid in 2021.

2.       The other issue is the pro rata distributions based on a percentag=
e of the trust rather than the specific bequest dollar amounts.  If we file=
d a final return in 2020, you would have to report 30% of the income and th=
ere is an issue of the capital loss carryover from prior years.  In general=
, all income and carryovers will be split between the final beneficiaries s=
o I will need to research further whether the 70% carryover capital loss th=
at is allocable to the charity and will have no tax benefit.

3.       MA return:  MA does not allow the election for the charitable dedu=
ction paid in the following year to be taken in the current year.   However=
, income that is not from MA sources that is accumulated for charity or non=
resident beneficiaries are not taxable at the trust level for MA purposes. =
 The residual estate is divided as 10% to Joshua, 20% to Sheryl and 70% to =
charity.  Therefore, all of the income is accumulated for a nonresident ind=
ividuals or charity and is not taxed in MA at the trust level.  The excepti=
on is MA source income.  Most of the trust income is the pass through IRA i=
ncome from the estate.  IRAs are not considered MA source income.  As a res=
ult of this provision, you will receive a refund of the extension payment. =
 The refund will be offset by the fact that the tax was paid in  2021.  How=
ever, the refund is over $600 and should be reported on a final 2021 tax re=
turn.


I would suggest that you set aside $1,000 to cover 2021 tax preparation fee=
s. We will bill you for 2020 return preparation when the return is complete=
d.  The draft 2020 Federal return shows a balance due of $2,206.  The fact =
that the charity is only entitled to 70% of the trust residue means that th=
e trust should only be able to deduct the 70% of the income allocable to th=
e charity.  If the two of you were only getting specific bequests, all of t=
he income would be allocable to charity.  It is a technical distinction and=
 the split was not clear at the time of the extension.

If you are not able to distribute most of the remaining assets by December =
31, 2021, there should not be any net income for 2021 to create a reporting=
 issue for the accumulation for charity. We will plan on filing a final ret=
urn for the trust for the 2021 tax year.

